emotional burdens.Through a detailed and colorful narrative, Endelman considers the social settings, national contexts, and historical circumstances that encouraged Jews to abandon Judaism, and factors that worked to the opposite effect. Demonstrating that anti-Jewish prejudice weighed more heavily on the Jews of Germany and Austria than those living in France and other liberal states as early as the first half of the nineteenth century, he reexamines how Germany's political and social development deviated from other European states. Endelman also reveals that liberal societies such as Great Britain and the United States, which tolerated Jewish integration, promoted radical assimilation and the dissolution of Jewish ties as often as hostile, illiberal societies such as Germany and Poland.Bringing together extensive research across several languages, Leaving the Jewish Fold will be the essential work on conversion and assimilation in modern Jewish history for years to come.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 27. Jan 2023) 0aChristian converts from JudaismxHistory. 0aChristian converts from JudaismzEuropexHistory. 0aJewsxConversion to ChristianityxHistory. 0aJewsxConversion to ChristianityzEuropexHistory. 0aJewsxConversion to Christianity. 0aJewsxCultural assimilationzEurope. 0aJewsxCultural assimilation. 0aJewsxIdentity. 0aJewszEuropexIdentity. 7aHISTORY / Jewish.2bisacsh  aAcculturation.  aAmerican Jews.  aAntisemitism (authors).  aAntisemitism.  aApostasy.  aArthur Ruppin.  aBenjamin Disraeli.  aBourgeoisie.  aBritish Jews.  aCareer.  aCatholic Church.  aCatholicism.  aCentral Europe.  aChristendom.  aChristian.  aChristianity and Judaism.  aChristianity.  aClergy.  aConscription.  aConversion to Judaism.  aCourt Jew.  aDefection.  aDominican Order.  aDowry